\begin_layout Standard
Before anything else, let us initially consider the case of an 
\emph on
infinity
\emph default
 wire.
 For starters, we show in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:finite_static_bands}}$
\end_inset

) how the SOC influences the energy-momentum band dispersion, plotting in
 colors the band structure with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{R}}>0$
\end_inset

 and in subtle gray with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{R}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Showcased is the shallow and deep electron band (in red) and the respective
 time-reversed hole's bands 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{h\pm}=-E_{e\pm}$
\end_inset

 (in blue).
 On the left we set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}=\Delta_{0}=\mu=0$
\end_inset

 to highlight the SOC behavior as it goes from a spinless regime to a helical
 one as the spin-
\begin_inset Formula $\uparrow$
\end_inset

 and spin-
\begin_inset Formula $\downarrow$
\end_inset

 bands mitose apart.
 
\color purple

\begin_inset Formula $\bigstar$
\end_inset

 canting 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigstar$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-wave to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-wave.
 
\color inherit
On the right, we specifically set the value of the Zeeman splitting to it's
 critical value 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}^{c}=\sqrt{\mu^{2}+\Delta_{0}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 (having nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

), where the band gap at 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 closes up.
 It's the closing and reopening of the gap at 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 that signals the trivial-topological phase transition.
 This type of phase transition is said to not be symmetry protected system,
 meaning that it isn't possible to go from a topological state to a trivial
 one without going through a closing of gap.
 Furthermore, see that as one accounts for SOC effects there is an additional
 minigap that opens ups on the outer wings.
 Thus, for values 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}<V_{\text{Z}}^{c}$
\end_inset

 the nanowire is in it's trivial phase, having a superconducting gap and
 being no longer spinless, while for values 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}^{c}>V_{C}$
\end_inset

 the nanowire is in it's topological phase, opening up a minigap due to
 the combined affects of Zeeman and SOC, eliminating the possibility of
 high-momentum gapless excitations, leaving only the chiral states near
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 as low energy excitation.
\end_layout

