\begin_layout Section
self-consistent nanowires
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a step up to the minimal Majorana model, in place of statically fixing
 the pairing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

, we instead solve for it self-consistent.
 Thus, in place of the superconductive proximity effect term in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:H}}$
\end_inset

), we use instead the on-site Hubbard mean-field self-energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{ij}$
\end_inset

 as derived in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:U}}$
\end_inset

).
 This model is pictorially depicted in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:SC_infinite}}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although looking for Majoranas physics, we first focus on the infinite length
 nanowire case because it is a lot less numerically expensive and because
 it lays out the groundwork analysis without muddying it with finite length
 effects, which unnecessarily complicates the analysis.
