\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We self-consistently obtain the rDM through the Hamiltonian's Green's function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

 for the finite case through a spectrum diagonalization, so basically 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=-i(\epsilon+i\eta-H)^{-1}$
\end_inset

, and for the infinite case through a generalized Schur's factorization
 relying on the numerical integration over Bloch phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{dn}=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi}^{+\pi}d\phi f(H(\phi)-\mu I)e^{idn\phi}$
\end_inset

 where the Fermi function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 of the Bloch Hamiltonian is computed via exact diagonalization at each
 Bloch phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 
\color purple

\begin_inset Formula $\bigstar$
\end_inset

 finite temperature? 
\color inherit
As a side-note, it it important that one forcefully imposes on every iteration
 of the self-consistency the BdG particle-hole symmetries as expressed rightly
 after Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:rho}}$
\end_inset

) because numerical errors will progressively drive the result to break
 those symmetries, even though they are self-imposed in the original Hamiltonian.

\color purple
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:infinite_MD}}$
\end_inset

), we first study the phase diagrams of the superconductive and magnetic
 correlation, corresponding respectively to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\rho_{i\uparrow j\downarrow}^{\text{eh}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M=(\rho_{i\uparrow j\uparrow}^{\text{ee}}-\rho_{i\downarrow j\downarrow}^{\text{ee}})/2$
\end_inset

, as one tunes the on-site Hubbard potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 versus the the chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and as one tunes the chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 versus the Zeeman field strength.
 The analysis boils down to the ongoing competition between those two quantities
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Looking at Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:infinite_MD}}$
\end_inset

)(left) we see that, for a given reasonable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $U<0$
\end_inset

 then only 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 is non-zero and the system is in it's superconductive phase and if 
\begin_inset Formula $U>0$
\end_inset

 then only 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 in non-zero and the system is in it's ferromagnetic phase.
 Note that while 
\begin_inset Formula $U<0$
\end_inset

 is always a prerequisite for superconductive, it alone does not guarantee
 it.
 Firstly because a strong enough external magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 would still magnetize the system and secondly because BCS theory tells
 us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{\text{BCS}}\approx\omega_{\text{D}}e^{(-Un_{\text{F}}a_{0})^{-1}}$
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{F}}$
\end_inset

 being the density of states at the Fermi level which in 1D decreases as
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 increases, thus meaning that also for a sufficient large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 superconducting dies out.
 On another matter, in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:infinite_MD}}$
\end_inset

)(right) we show how the superconductive correlation behaves during the
 topological phase transitions.
 In this case the phase transition (traced in black) is found through the
 abrupt change in value of Kitaev's "Majorana number" 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, being either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\mathcal{M}}=+1$
\end_inset

 in the trivial case or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=-1$
\end_inset

 in the topological case (applicable only in the case of open boundary condition
s) [?].
 For general non-interacting systems, the fermionic parity 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of the ground state of a Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 can be shown to take the form 
\begin_inset Formula $P(H)=\text{sgn}(\text{Pf}(A))$
\end_inset

 with the Pfaffian 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Pf}$
\end_inset

 a function of a skew-symmetric matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\text{Pf}(A))^{2}=\text{det}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 For this reason, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is also referred to as the Pffafian 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

 invariant.
\end_layout

